></div></div></div></div><div class="e979f264" data-scp="callout_pointer"></div></div><p>The pots and pans in the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/161752/4/109401/?merchant=Home%20Depot" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Home Depot" data-vars-store="Home Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/161752/4/109401/?merchant=Home%20Depot">Tramontina Gourmet 12-Piece Tri-Ply Clad Cookware Set</a><a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17417/139227/4/59237/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17417/139227/4/59237/?merchant=Amazon"></a> heat evenly and have a comfortable weight so they aren’t cumbersome to lift. Their rounded, ergonomically shaped handles are comfortable to hold. We’ve long-term tested an older (now discontinued) version of this set for two years, and we’re confident that this durable cookware set will provide you with many years of use.</p><p>If you&#x27;re unable to find the full set in stock, Tramontina also sells its cookware open stock, which means you can build your own set for around the same price. Here are the pieces we’d get to build a good 10-piece set:</p><ul><li>A <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38277/161565/4/113717/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38277/161565/4/113717/?merchant=Amazon">1.5-quart</a> or <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/32150/153268/4/113718/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" dat