tent/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4903-200x134.jpg"/></figure><p class="_0e697247" data-scp="caption">We simmered large batches of tomato sauce in the stockpots to test for scorching.<!-- --> <span class=" ">Photo: Michael Hession</span></p></li><li aria-hidden="false" style="width:570px;margin-right:0;float:left;display:block"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="cookwear sets pot drip test" class="fc20a4b4 df5db67b _45d01177" itemProp="image" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4909-570x380.jpg" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4909-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4909-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4909-200x134.jpg 200w" data-amp-layout="responsive" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4909-200x134.jpg"/></figure><p class="_0e697247" data-scp="caption">We checked to see if the pots dripped while we poured sauce into quart containers.<!-- --> <span class=" ">Photo: Michael Hession</span></p></li><li class="_6c50919b" data-scp="inline_gallery_item_clone" aria-hidden="true" style="width:570px;margin-right:0;float:left;display:block"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="cookwear sets caramel preparation" class="fc20a4b4 df5db67b _45d01177" itemProp="image" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4895-570x380.jpg" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4895-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4895-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4895-200x134.jpg 200w" data-amp-layout="responsive" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-4895-200x134.jpg"/></figure><p class="_0e697247" data-scp="caption">We prepared small batches of caramel in the saucepans to check for hot spots.<!-- --> <span class=" ">Photo: Michael Hession</span></p></li></ul></div></div><div class="c2afacaf" data-scp="gallery_meta"><div class="_6563c784"><span class="current-slide">1</span> of <!-- -->5</div><div class="_075942f0"><span class="_23038fc4"></span><span class="ce98be6c"></span></div></div></figure><p>Additionally, we evaluated how easy the handles were to hold, especially when retrieving the pots and pans from a hot oven using a side towel or pot holders. We also took note of the individual weight and thickness of the pieces in each set. To test for dripping, we observed how easily we could pour liquids from each pot. By hand-washing the pots and pans, we got a sense of how easy they were to clean. And we looked at how well each set nested for convenient storage.</p></div></section><section class="e1e9ed3a" id="our-pick-tramontina-gourmet-tri-ply-clad-12-piece-cookware-set"><h2 class="_60d21928" aria-controls="our-pick-tramontina-gourmet-tri-ply-clad-12-piece-cookware-set-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading">Our pick: Tramontina Gourmet Tri-Ply Clad 12-Piece Cookware Set<button class="_26f76ff6" aria-expanded="true" aria-pressed="false" aria-haspopup="false" data-scp="chapter_toggle"></button></h2><div id="our-pick-tramontina-gourmet-tri-ply-clad-12-piece-cookware-set-panel" class="_621a71d4" aria-labelledby="our-pick-tramontina-gourmet-tri-ply-clad-12-piece-cookware-set" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="The Tramontina 12-piece set." width="636" height="424" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 alignnone wp-image-141012 size-full" data-sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374.jpg 636w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-630x420.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5374-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><div class="a7ed89b1 global-cob eefda761 cff8e815" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="b1dfff67" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-0-2" class="f4873f0f" data-gtm-element="callout" data-scp="callout_item"><div class="_32e239ce"><div class="_892e4e17"><div class="a35ae31e"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" class="bac232ef product-merchant-link-button" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-store="Wayfair" data-vars-store="Wayfair" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="callout_image"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="Tramontina Gourmet 12-Piece Tri-Ply Clad Cookware Set" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/36738/Tramontina-Gourmet-12-Piece-Tri-Ply-Clad-Cookware-Set_20201001-182156_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="df5db67b _45d01177"/></figure></a></div><div class="d3181b64"><h3 class="_8eb8c80e"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" class="product-link" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="Tramontina Gourmet 12-Piece Tri-Ply Clad Cookware Set" data-store="Wayfair" data-vars-store="Wayfair" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product">Tramontina Gourmet 12-Piece Tri-Ply Clad Cookware Set</a></h3><h2 class="b60192a2"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" class="product-merchant-link-button" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="The best cookware set" data-store="Wayfair" data-vars-store="Wayfair" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title">The best cookware set</a></h2><p class="e47abd0b" data-scp="callout_description">This affordable fully-clad tri-ply set distributes heat evenly and is durable enough to take some abuse in a busy household.</p><div data-scp="callout_sources"><h4 class="_458e2800">Buying Options</h4><div class="_5e08d7c5 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" class="_157bb603 product-merchant-link-button" data-store="Wayfair" data-vars-store="Wayfair" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/163977/4/111078?merchant=Wayfair" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$260</span> from <span>Wayfair</span></a></div><div class="_5e08d7c5 product-pricebox-1" data-source-id-order="1" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/161752/4/111078?merchant=Home%20Depot" class="_157bb603 product-merchant-link-button" data-store="Home Depot" data-vars-store="Home Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/161752/4/111078?merchant=Home%20Depot" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button">Buy<!-- --> from <span>Home Depot</span></a><p class="f920dbab">May be out of stock</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><p>We like the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/161752/4/109401/?merchant=Home%20Depot" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Home Depot" data-vars-store="Home Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36738/161752/4/109401/?merchant=Home%20Depot">Tramontina Gourmet 12-Piece Tri-Ply Clad Cookware Set</a> for its even heat distribution, durable construction, and affordable price. The Tramontina skillets produced perfectly brown chicken pieces with nice fond development, and the saucepans and stockpot simmered liquids without scorching. We found the wide handles on both the cookware and the lids comfortable to hold. Though this cookware discolored over high heat, the effect was common among all of the sets we tested in this price range. All of the cookware in this collection is dishwasher-safe, induction-compatible, and oven-safe up to 500 degrees Fahrenheit.</p><p>Included in this Tramontina set are 12 pieces: 8- and 10-inch skillets, a 6-quart deep sauté pan with a lid, 1½-, 2-, and 3-quart saucepans with lids, and an 8-quart stockpot with a lid. Though we wish this set included a larger 12-inch skillet instead of an 8-inch skillet, the 6-quart deep sauté pan is 11¾ inches in diameter (and about 3¼ inches deep), so it comfortably fits a whole chicken cut up. If you want to grow your set, the Tramontina 12-inch skillet can be purchased separately—we recommend it as our runner-up pick in <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-skillet/">our guide to the best skillet</a>. Alternatively, all of these pieces are sold open stock, so you can piece together your own version of this set with just the pieces that you want (If we were to do that, we&#x27;d skip the 8-inch skillet, and get a 10-inch and a 12-inch skillet instead).</p><figure id="attachment_141013" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="The Tramontina 12-piece set including an 8-quart stockpot with a lid, 3-, 2-, and 1½-quart saucepans with lids, 8- and 10-inch skillets, and a 6-quart deep sauté pan with a lid." width="636" height="424" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 wp-image-141013 size-full" data-sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288.jpg 636w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-630x420.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5288-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> The Tramontina 12-piece set includes (clockwise from top left): an 8-quart stockpot with a lid, 3-, 2-, and 1½-quart saucepans with lids, 8- and 10-inch skillets, and a 6-quart deep sauté pan with a lid.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Sarah Kobos</span></figcaption></figure><p>In our tests, the Tramontina 3-quart saucepan made perfect caramel without burning, though some of our testers found they had to swirl the pan more to distribute the heat evenly. The stockpot didn’t scorch while simmering tomato sauce. To compare, this wasn’t the case with the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17420/53893/4/59240/?merchant=Amazon&amp;merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17420/53893/4/59240/?merchant=Amazon&amp;merchant=Amazon">Cuisinart Chef’s Classic</a> stockpot, which required frequent stirring to prevent the sauce from burning. Also, the 10-inch Tramontina skillet made perfectly golden-brown chicken breasts with extra-crispy skin.</p><figure id="attachment_141015" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="The Tramontina set stacked up." width="636" height="424" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 wp-image-141015 size-full" data-sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358.jpg 636w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-630x420.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5358-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> The Tramontina set has more pieces than our upgrade pick, the All-Clad 10-Piece Set, but it still stacks well if you plan to store it in a cupboard.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Sarah Kobos</span></figcaption></figure><p>Our testers also liked the weight of the pieces in the Tramontina set, which felt durable enough to withstand the rigors of daily cooking. The handles on the stainless steel lids were big enough to grab onto, even when we used a side towel or pot holders. We also found that the stick handles were comfortable to hold and the appropriate length, unlike the handles on the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17424/53902/4/59243/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17424/53902/4/59243/?merchant=Amazon">Anolon Tri-Ply Clad Stainless Steel 12-Piece Cookware Set</a>, which were too short.</p><p>This Tramontina set comes with a lifetime warranty that covers manufacturer defects. If you encounter problems with this cookware under normal household use, contact <a href="https://www.tramontina-usa.com/contact/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Tramontina</a> for a replacement.</p><h3>Long-term test notes:</h3><p>We’ve long-term tested an older (now discontinued) version of this set for two years, and all of the pots and pans continue to distribute heat evenly. The skillets have become a bit more discolored after searing meat over high heat, but their performance remains the same.</p></div></section><section class="e1e9ed3a" id="flaws-but-not-dealbreakers"><h2 class="_60d21928" aria-controls="flaws-but-not-dealbreakers-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading">Flaws but not dealbreakers<button class="_26f76ff6" aria-expanded="true" aria-pressed="false" aria-haspopup="false" data-scp="chapter_toggle"></button></h2><div id="flaws-but-not-dealbreakers-panel" class="_621a71d4" aria-labelledby="flaws-but-not-dealbreakers" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><p>As with most of the sets we tested in this price range, the Tramontina skillets tarnished after normal use. Although we easily removed burned-on oil and food bits using a combination of baking soda and warm water, the pans retained a noticeable tint after cleaning. Because the discoloration in no way affects the cooking performance, we’re willing to forgive this minor drawback.</p></div></section><section class="e1e9ed3a" id="upgrade-pick-all-clad-stainless-10-piece-set"><h2 class="_60d21928" aria-controls="upgrade-pick-all-clad-stainless-10-piece-set-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading">Upgrade pick: All-Clad Stainless 10-Piece Set<button class="_26f76ff6" aria-expanded="true" aria-pressed="false" aria-haspopup="false" data-scp="chapter_toggle"></button></h2><div id="upgrade-pick-all-clad-stainless-10-piece-set-panel" class="_621a71d4" aria-labelledby="upgrade-pick-all-clad-stainless-10-piece-set" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><figure id="attachment_141016" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" width="636" height="424" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 wp-image-141016 size-full" data-sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205.jpg 636w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-630x420.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5205-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> The All-Clad Stainless 10-Piece Set.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Sarah Kobos</span></figcaption></figure><div class="a7ed89b1 global-cob cff8e815" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="b1dfff67" data-scp="callout_label">Upgrade pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-4-1" class="f4873f0f" data-gtm-element="callout" data-scp="callout_item"><div class="_32e239ce"><div class="_892e4e17"><div class="a35ae31e"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" class="bac232ef product-merchant-link-button" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="callout_image"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="All-Clad Tri-Ply Stainless Steel 10-Piece Set" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/17421/All-Clad-Tri-Ply-Stainless-Steel-10-Piece-Set_20170802-182318_fullsize.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="df5db67b _45d01177"/></figure></a></div><div class="d3181b64"><h3 class="_8eb8c80e"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" class="product-link" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="All-Clad Tri-Ply Stainless Steel 10-Piece Set" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product">All-Clad Tri-Ply Stainless Steel 10-Piece Set</a></h3><h2 class="b60192a2"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" class="product-merchant-link-button" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="A buy-it-for-life cookware set" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title">A buy-it-for-life cookware set</a></h2><p class="e47abd0b" data-scp="callout_description">The pans in this top-of-the-line set continue to impress us with their even heat distribution. Each piece of cookware is extremely durable and the ideal weight to hold.</p><div data-scp="callout_sources"><h4 class="_458e2800">Buying Options</h4><div class="_5e08d7c5 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" class="_157bb603 product-merchant-link-button" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/74853?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$700</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><p>You’ll likely never have to replace the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/59241/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17421/53965/4/59241/?merchant=Amazon">All-Clad Stainless 10-Piece Set</a>. It was hands down the best-quality cookware we tested in this price range ($700 at the time of testing). The pots and pans have the perfect weight, and they cooked food more evenly than our top-pick set due to their superior heat conduction. This cookware set was one of the only ones that turned out spotlessly clean after washing, even when coated with burned-on oil. And although this set is much more expensive than our main pick, we think it’s worth the extra cost for its durability and proven longevity.</p><p>The All-Clad Stainless 10-Piece Set includes 8- and 10-inch skillets, 2- and 3-quart saucepans with lids, a 3-quart sauté pan with a lid, and an 8-quart stockpot with a lid. The only drawback to this set is that it doesn’t include a <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/7918/23270/4/59255/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/7918/23270/4/59255/?merchant=Amazon">12-inch skillet</a>, but we don’t think this omission is a dealbreaker, because you can always grow your collection by adding that piece down the road. (We also recommend the 12-inch All-Clad pan, which is our top pick in <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-skillet/">our guide to the best skillet</a>.) All of the pieces in this set are dishwasher safe, induction compatible, and oven safe up to 500 degrees Fahrenheit.</p><figure id="attachment_141017" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="The All-Clad Stainless 10-Piece Set pieces." width="636" height="424" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 wp-image-141017 size-full" data-sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167.jpg 636w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-630x420.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5167-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> The All-Clad Stainless 10-Piece Set includes (clockwise from top left): an 8-quart stockpot with a lid, 3- and 2-quart saucepans with lids, an 8-inch skillet, a 10-inch skillet, and a 3-quart sauté pan with a lid.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Sarah Kobos</span></figcaption></figure><p>Most of our testers liked the angle of the stick handles in the All-Clad set, which have a rounded bottom that fits nicely in your hand even when you’re holding a dish towel or pot holder. However, some preferred the thicker, rounded handles of the Tramontina set. We also found the handles on the lids easy to grab, unlike those of the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17431/53931/4/59248/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17431/53931/4/59248/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond">Mauviel M’cook set</a>, which were tiny.</p><figure id="attachment_11301" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="cookwear sets all-clad tri-ply handle" width="630" height="420" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 size-full wp-image-11301" data-sizes="(max-width: 630px) 100vw, 630px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5268-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> Our testers liked the angle of the stick handles in the All-Clad set, which have a rounded bottom that fits nicely in your hand.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Michael Hession</span></figcaption></figure><p>In our tests, the chicken sautéed in the All-Clad 10-inch skillet cooked evenly and turned out perfectly golden brown with a crispy skin, about on a par with the chicken we made in the Tramontina skillet. When we prepared caramel, the dissolved sugar bubbled uniformly across the bottom of the All-Clad 3-quart saucepan, which wasn’t the case with the other sets we tested. Also, because the saucepan distributed heat so well, our testers didn’t have to swirl the sugar in the pan as frequently as they did in the saucepans from other sets. There was no scorching in the stockpot while simmering tomato sauce, even with minimal stirring. We noticed that some tomato sauce dripped down the side of the stockpot while we poured, but there were no splatters on the counter.</p><aside class="a869c42a"><p data-scp="pullquote">All-Clad was the name that came up again and again when we spoke to the pros.</p></aside><p>If you’re partial to keeping your cookware looking bright and shiny, note that this was one of the only sets we tested that looked like new after cleaning. Though burned-on oil or grease can be more challenging to remove with just regular dish soap or a run through the dishwasher, <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9283/26543/4/74845/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9283/26543/4/74845/?merchant=Amazon">Bar Keepers Friend</a> or a slurry of baking soda and warm water applied with a nonabrasive sponge (and a little elbow grease) gets the job done. The All-Clad skillets discolored slightly over heat, though significantly less than almost any other cookware we tested.</p><figure id="attachment_11302" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="cookwear all-clad cleaning results" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-clean.gif" width="630" height="420" class="df5db67b _45d01177 size-full wp-image-11302"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> The All-Clad cookware was the only set we tested that looked like new after cleaning.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Michael Hession</span></figcaption></figure><p>Because it’s so durable, All-Clad was the name that came up again and again when we spoke to the pros. Chef Candy Argondizza, vice president of culinary and pastry arts at the International Culinary Center at the time of our interview, said, “Both professionally and personally, I use All-Clad.” Janet Crandall, a Los Angeles–based private chef and cooking instructor, told us, “They are expensive, but worth it because of their durability.” Members of our own staff have owned or worked with All-Clad cookware for years, including writer and Wirecutter test kitchen manager Lesley Stockton, who said, “My oldest All-Clad is nine years old, and it’s as good as the day I bought it. When I worked in the Martha Stewart test kitchen, we were cooking on All-Clad pieces that were at least 15 years old.”</p><figure id="attachment_141018" class="wp-caption alignnone"><figure class="_92ef929f global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="The All-Clad set stacked up." width="636" height="424" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-120x80.jpg" class="df5db67b _45d01177 size-full wp-image-141018" data-sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187.jpg 636w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-630x420.jpg 630w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-570x380.jpg 570w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-330x220.jpg 330w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-200x134.jpg 200w, https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/cookware-lowres-5187-120x80.jpg 120w"/></figure><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> The All-Clad set stacks well, so it takes up less space in a cupboard.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Sarah Kobos</span></figcaption></figure><p>All-Clad offers a wide range of cookware outside the main set, so you can grow your collection. We recommend several other All-Clad pieces in our cookware guides, including the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-skillet/#our-pick">12-inch skillet</a>, the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-nonstick-pan/#also-great-all-clad-b1-hard-anodized-nonstick-fry-pans-set">8- and 10-inch nonstick skillet</a>, the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-small-saucepan/#upgrade">2-quart saucier</a>, and the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-roasting-pan/#upgrade-pick-williams-sonoma-all-clad-stainless-steel-flared-roaster">flared roaster</a>. Check out the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.all-clad.com/Cookware/c/cookware_category" rel="noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Unknown" data-vars-store="Unknown" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.all-clad.com/Cookware/c/cookware_category">All-Clad website</a> to see a full list of its cookware.</p><p>The All-Clad tri-ply set is made in the US. (To learn more about how All-Clad cookware is made, check out David Lebovitz’s <a href="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/visit-all-clad-cookware-factory/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">blog post</a> about his factory tour in Pittsburgh.) The pans come with a limited lifetime warranty that covers manufacturer defects. Should you experience any problems with this set, contact <a href="http://www.all-clad.com/CustomerService/Contact-us" rel="noopener" target="_blank">All-Clad</a> for repairs or replacements.</p><h3>Long-term test notes:</h3><p>We continue to reach for All-Clad the most in the Wirecutter test kitchen. Several of our staff have worked with All-Clad pots and pans professionally, and find that they continue to heat evenly and clean up well, even after years of persistent use.</p></div></section><section class="e1e9ed3a" id="care-and-maintenance"><h2 class="_60d21928" aria-controls="care-and-maintenance-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading">Care and maintenance<button class="_26f76ff6" aria-expanded="true" aria-pressed="false" aria-haspopup="false" data-scp="chapter_toggle"></button></h2><div id="care-and-maintenance-panel" class="_621a71d4" aria-labelledby="care-and-maintenance" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><p>Though most stainless steel cookware is dishwasher safe, we recommend washing it by hand whenever possible. A sponge does a much better job of getting into the nooks and crannies of a pan (especially around where the handle meets the pan, or around rivets). For difficult-to-remove items like burnt-on oil or lime deposits, <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9283/26543/4/59256/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9283/26543/4/59256/?merchant=Amazon">Bar Keepers Friend</a> applied with a sponge usually does the trick. In the Wirecutter test kitchen, we often remove burnt-on oil or discoloration using a slurry of baking soda and warm water along with a sponge and a little elbow grease. For other cleaning options, refer to our <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/blog/how-to-clean-stainless-steel-pans/">blog post</a> and <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P16xnzCWiec" rel="noopener" target="_blank">video</a> on the subject.</p><p>Never clean your stainless steel cookware with harsh chemicals, such as oven cleaner, that could cause permanent damage. Also, avoid using steel wool, which can severely scratch your cookware.</p><p>It’s industry standard for cookware manufacturers to advise against cooking over high temperatures to avoid liability for damage caused by misuse. However, judging from our years of experience, as long as you reduce the heat after preheating your pan on medium or medium-high heat, you won’t damage your pans.</p><p>For information on how to prevent food from sticking to your stainless steel cookware, check out our <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/blog/food-sticking-pan/">blog post</a> on the subject.</p><p>If you’re worried about using metal utensils on your stainless steel cookware, don’t be: Although such tools may cause minor scratches on the surface of pots and pans, they will not damage the cookware’s performance.</p><p>Also, don’t place a screaming-hot pan under running water or in a sink to soak. Chef Janet Crandall told us, “I can’t stress enough the care of good cookware. NEVER put a hot pan or pot into water. Let them cool down. It doesn’t matter how much you spend on cookware, they will warp.”</p></div></section><section class="e1e9ed3a" id="the-competition"><h2 class="_60d21928" aria-controls="the-competition-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading">The competition<button class="_26f76ff6" aria-expanded="true" aria-pressed="false" aria-haspopup="false" data-scp="chapter_toggle"></button></h2><div id="the-competition-panel" class="_621a71d4" aria-labelledby="the-competition" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><h3>Priced between $80 to $550</h3><p>We like that the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/37266/159868/4/111082/?merchant=Sur%20La%20Table" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Sur La Table" data-vars-store="Sur La Table" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/37266/159868/4/111082/?merchant=Sur%20La%20Table">La Marque 84 10-Piece Stainless Steel Cookware Set</a> from Sur la Table includes 10- and 12-inch skillets, but we decided not to test it because it’s made of five-ply stainless steel. In our previous tests, we consistently found that five-ply cookware doesn’t usually heat as uniformly as regular tri-ply cookware, and it takes significantly longer to preheat. Also, the largest pot in this set is only 5 quarts, which isn’t big enough for boiling a large batch of pasta.</p><p>We opted not to test the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/37267/159869/4/111083/?merchant=Food52" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Food52" data-vars-store="Food52" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/37267/159869/4/111083/?merchant=Food52">Five Two Essential Cookware 11-Piece Complete Set</a> because it comes with glass lids and the stock pot is only 6 quarts. Also, this set comes with two ceramic non-stick skillets. <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-nonstick-pan/#types-of-nonstick-coatings">According to our research</a> ceramic coatings don’t last as long as PTFE coatings.</p><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17418/53875/4/59238/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17418/53875/4/59238/?merchant=Amazon">Cuisinart MultiClad Pro Stainless Steel 12-Piece Cookware Set</a> was our previous runner-up pick. However, after a new round of testing, we found the skillets warped over high heat. The bottom of the pans bowed out so much, they wobbled on a flat surface. We tested multiple skillets to be sure this wasn’t a fluke, but all of them had the same results. Although the pans were still usable after warping, their damage voids the warranty. The Cuisinart manual says to never use the cookware over high heat, recommending instead, “a low to medium setting for most cooking.” Many cookware manufacturers have the same recommendation, but our picks haven’t warped like the Cuisinart, even after years of cooking over high heat.</p><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17420/53893/4/59240/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17420/53893/4/59240/?merchant=Amazon">Cuisinart 77-7 Chef’s Classic Stainless 7-Piece Cookware Set</a> was our former budget pick. However, this set is prone to hot spots because it’s not fully clad. The single layer of stainless steel around the perimeter of the pan is too thin to evenly distribute heat and causes food to burn. We think that if you’re on a budget, you’re better off getting fewer, higher quality pieces of cookware that will give you better results and last longer. (Tramontina, our main pick, sells pieces from the set we recommend <a class="product-link" href="https://www.walmart.com/search/?query=tramontina%20tri-ply%20clad&amp;typeahead=tramontina" rel="noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Unknown" data-vars-store="Unknown" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.walmart.com/search/?query=tramontina%20tri-ply%20clad&amp;typeahead=tramontina">open stock at Walmart</a>.)</p><p>The design of the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17425/53912/4/59244/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17425/53912/4/59244/?merchant=Amazon">Cuisinart French Classic Stainless 10-Piece Cookware Set</a> gives the skillets higher sides that make tossing vegetables a bit more challenging than with our top picks. In addition, for the price, we wish this set came with a second skillet.</p><p>The stick handles on the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17424/53902/4/59243/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17424/53902/4/59243/?merchant=Amazon">Anolon Tri-Ply Clad Stainless Steel 12-Piece Cookware Set</a> were too short and less comfortable to hold than the wide, longer handles on the Tramontina cookware.</p><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17426/53920/4/59245/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17426/53920/4/59245/?merchant=Amazon">Duxtop Whole Clad Tri ply Stainless Steel Premium 10-Piece Cookware Set</a> did poorly in our caramel test, as areas of the saucepan started to burn the sugar before the center had fully dissolved. This set also dripped the most when we poured liquids.</p><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26483/139097/4/74846/?merchant=Made%20In" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Made In" data-vars-store="Made In" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26483/139097/4/74846/?merchant=Made%20In">Made In Kitchen Sink set</a> did well in our tests. However, most of our testers found the stick handles on the skillets to be uncomfortably low, preferring the higher angle of the handles on our picks. At the time of our testing, the Made In cookware had cooking instructions etched on the bottom of the pans, which we felt was a bit cheesy, especially if you plan to hang them on a wall (and not particularly helpful while you’re using the pans). However, according to the representative we spoke to, Made In stopped producing cookware with these etchings beginning in 2018.</p><p>We dismissed the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26484/139098/4/74847/?merchant=Walmart" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Walmart" data-vars-store="Walmart" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26484/139098/4/74847/?merchant=Walmart">Cooks Standard Multi-Ply Clad Stainless Steel 12-piece Cookware Set</a> because the rivets weren’t secure on some of the pot handles, which caused them to wiggle.</p><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/34483/156370/4/100347/?merchant=Potluck" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Potluck" data-vars-store="Potluck" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/34483/156370/4/100347/?merchant=Potluck">Potluck cookware set</a> comes with just seven pieces, and only includes a 10-inch skillet, so we decided not to test it. If you’re going to get just one skillet, we think a 12-inch pan is the more versatile option. Plus, the Tramontina set we recommend doesn’t cost much more than the Potluck set, and includes almost twice as many pieces.</p><p>We ruled out the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/34521/156412/4/100354/?merchant=Misen" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Misen" data-vars-store="Misen" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/34521/156412/4/100354/?merchant=Misen">cookware sets from Misen</a> after testing the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/32154/153272/4/100348/?merchant=Misen" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Misen" data-vars-store="Misen" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/32154/153272/4/100348/?merchant=Misen">Misen 3QT Saucier</a> in our guide to <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-small-saucepan/">the best small saucepan</a>. Its five-ply construction made the pan slower to heat up and its tubular handle was hard to hold onto. We’ve also watched Misen’s cookware go in and out of stock frequently.</p><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/34523/156414/4/100357/?merchant=Great%20Jones" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Great Jones" data-vars-store="Great Jones" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/34523/156414/4/100357/?merchant=Great%20Jones">Great Jones Family Style set</a> is unusual among the cookware sets we looked at in that it includes a nonstick pan and an enameled cast iron Dutch oven. However, we decided not to test it for a few reasons. For one, after testing the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/32155/153273/4/100358/?merchant=Great%20Jones" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Great Jones" data-vars-store="Great Jones" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/32155/153273/4/100358/?merchant=Great%20Jones">Great Jones Saucy</a> for our guide to <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-small-saucepan/">the best small saucepan</a>, we found the company’s loop-shaped handles uncomfortable to hold. Also, the nonstick pan is only 8.5 inches, so it’s not as versatile as the 10-inch pans we recommend in our guide to nonstick skillets, and it has a ceramic coating, which we’ve found quickly loses its nonstick properties. The set’s only other skillet, a 10.25-inch skillet/sauté pan hybrid, is also on the small side.</p><h3>Priced between $600 to $800</h3><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17430/53930/4/59247/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17430/53930/4/59247/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma">All-Clad d5 Brushed Stainless 10-Piece Set</a> held onto heat more, so it took longer for us to make caramel and achieve nicely golden-brown chicken. This set also costs $100 more than our upgrade pick.</p><p>Although the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17431/53931/4/59248/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17431/53931/4/59248/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond">Mauviel M’cook Stainless Steel 9-Piece Cookware Set</a> performed well in our tests, it includes a small, 1-quart saucepan, which we felt was more limiting than a 1½- or 2-quart saucepan. On top of that, the lids have tiny handles that we found difficult to grasp, and the set comes with only one skillet.</p><p>We previously tested the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17437/53956/4/59257/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17437/53956/4/59257/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond">12½-inch skillet</a> from the Breville Thermal Pro line for <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/the-best-skillet/">our guide to the best skillet</a>. The Breville weighed almost 5 pounds and retained too much heat due to its thick base, which made temperature control difficult. Based on those results, we opted not to test the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17490/54212/4/59258/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-store="Bed Bath &amp; Beyond" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17490/54212/4/59258/?merchant=Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond">Breville Thermal Pro Clad Stainless 10-Piece Cookware Set</a> in this roundup.</p><p>The skillets in the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17439/53957/4/59259/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17439/53957/4/59259/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma">Williams Sonoma Signature Thermo-Clad Stainless-Steel 10-Piece Cookware Set</a> have a very small cooking surface. The handles on this set are also very long, which we found awkward—especially on a crowded range. At 3 pounds, 14.8 ounces, the Signature Thermo-Clad pan was a bit hefty for some of our testers.</p><h3>Priced over $800</h3><p>We were curious to see if the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17441/165614/4/74850/?merchant=Amazon" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17441/165614/4/74850/?merchant=Amazon">Demeyere 5-Plus 10-Piece Cookware Set</a> was worth its exorbitant price. In our tests, the pans heated incredibly evenly and didn’t discolor over high heat. However, the pans took almost double the time to preheat as our picks and were heavier than we’d prefer. We think this set is worth the steep price only if you’re looking for rivetless cookware.</p><p>Because copper is such an excellent conductor of heat, we decided to test the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/24521/130679/4/74851/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/24521/130679/4/74851/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma">All-Clad Copper Core 10-Piece Set</a> to see how it would perform against regular tri-ply stainless steel cookware. In our tests, the copper-core cookware heated up so fast we had to swirl the pan more when making caramel to prevent it from burning. Unlike the tri-ply All-Clad set we recommend, the Copper Core skillets discolored badly over high heat.</p><p>We tested the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26485/165599/4/74848/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-store="Williams-Sonoma" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26485/165599/4/74848/?merchant=Williams-Sonoma">Hestan 12.5″ Open Skillet</a> to see if its <a href="https://www.hestanculinary.com/nanobond/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">NanoBond Technology</a> made it less prone to discoloration than other cookware. The pan discolored slightly in our tests, but was easy to clean with the Hestan brand stainless steel cleaner. However, because the skillet concentrated heat in the center of the pan, we opted not to try the full <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26486/139100/4/74849/?merchant=Hestan" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Hestan" data-vars-store="Hestan" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/26486/139100/4/74849/?merchant=Hestan">Hestan 10-Piece Set</a>. Also, this set costs a whopping $1,500 (at the time of testing). For half the price, we think anyone would be happy with the All-Clad set we recommend.</p></div></section><section class="e1e9ed3a" id="sources"><h2 class="_60d21928" aria-controls="sources-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading">Sources<button class="_26f76ff6" aria-expanded="true" aria-pressed="false" aria-haspopup="false" data-scp="chapter_toggle"></button></h2><div id="sources-panel" class="_621a71d4 f8952f12" aria-labelledby="sources" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><ol class="_50324be4"><li class="_4277734e" data-scp="sources_item"><p data-scp="sources_content"><a href="http://www.cooksillustrated.com/equipment_reviews/1163-cookware-sets?ref=new_search_experience_1&amp;incode=MCSCD00L0" target="_blank" title="Cookware Sets">Cookware Sets</a>, Cook’s Illustrated (subscription required)</p></li><li class="_4277734e" data-scp="sources_item"><p data-scp="sources_content"><a href="http://cookware.org/buyers-learning-tools/" target="_blank" title="Buyers’ Learning Tools">Buyers’ Learning Tools</a>, Cookware Manufacturers Association</p></li><li class="_4277734e" data-scp="sources_item"><p data-scp="sources_content">Candy Argondizza, <a href="http://www.internationalculinarycenter.com/" target="_blank" title="then vice president of culinary and pastry arts at International Culinary Center">then vice president of culinary and pastry arts at International Culinary Center</a>, email interview<!-- -->, July 27, 2016</p></li><li class="_4277734e" data-scp="sources_item"><p data-scp="sources_content">Janet Crandall, <a href="http://chefjanetcrandall.com/#about-chef-janet" target="_blank" ti