","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Though most people are inclined to buy sets because doing so is cheaper than buying pieces individually, sets involve a compromise. Most manufacturers cut corners by including smaller pot and pan sizes in a set to reduce the overall price. Rushing told us that “shrinking the pot and pan sizes might only be a 5 or 6 percent difference in cost [for the manufacturer], but it drops the bottom line.” Smaller pan sizes require you to cook in batches and can slow you down in the kitchen. Candy Argondizza, then vice president of culinary and pastry arts at International Culinary Center, told us, “Sets often sell you pieces that you don’t need. I like to pick and choose what I want. It might be a little more expensive this way, but space is a commodity in my tiny kitchen, so I choose what I need wisely.” Janet Crandall, a Los Angeles private chef and cooking instructor, agreed, saying, “I prefer to buy individual pans. Sometimes sets don’t always have the exact size I want.”","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Both Argondizza and Crandall gave suggestions for the best pot and pan sizes to look for. Note that the number of pieces advertised in a set includes lids, so you’re generally getting half the listed number of pots and pans. A good set should include the following 10 pieces:","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"ul","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"li","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"strong","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"1.5- to 2-quart saucepan with a lid:","type":"text"}]},{"data":" For reheating a small amount of soup or melting butter","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"li","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"strong","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"3- to 4-quart saucepan with a lid:","type":"text"}]},{"data":" For making sauces or reheating stocks and soups","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"li","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"strong","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"8- and 10-inch or 10- and 12-inch skillets:","type":"text"}]},{"data":" For searing meats and sautéing vegetables","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"li","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"strong","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"3- to 4-quart skillet with a lid:","type":"text"}]},{"data":" For quickly reducing sauces, making roux, and preparing shallow braises","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"li","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"strong","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"8-quart (or larger) stockpot with a lid:","type":"text"}]},{"data":" For boiling water for pasta, handling large-batch sauces, or making stocks, soups, and stews","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"We found that most skillets in sets are only 8 to 10 inches, but we prefer 10- and 12-inch versions because they offer a larger surface area for cooking more at once. This was one of the factors that set our previous pick from Tramontina (which has now been discontinued) apart from the competition. Our new pick is a very similar set from Tramontina, but it includes 8- and 10-inch skillets. Unfortunately, we weren’t able to find any other sets that included 10- and 12-inch skillets and also met our other requirements. Many sets also have stockpots that are only 6 quarts, which is too small for making large batches of stock (8-quart or larger stockpots are best for preparing stocks and provide ample room for boiling pasta). The smaller pan sizes offered in most sets are the main incentive for buying what you need piece by piece.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"shortcode-pullquote","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"After years of long-term testing, we don’t think you can get a quality set for under $250.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"You can always purchase other essential pieces, such as a ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-dutch-oven/"},"children":[{"data":"Dutch oven","type":"text"}]},{"data":", a ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-cast-iron-skillet/"},"children":[{"data":"cast iron skillet","type":"text"}]},{"data":", and a ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-nonstick-pan/"},"children":[{"data":"nonstick pan","type":"text"}]},{"data":", in addition to your main set. Don’t be tempted to buy huge sets with lots of pieces. Most of the pots and pans in those larger sets are just filler. Ultimately, those pieces won’t see much use and will only clutter up your kitchen. Our experts agreed that you’re better off getting a set with fewer but better-quality pieces you’ll reach for again and again.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"h3","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Comfortable weight","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"The ideal weight and balance of cookware will be different for everyone. However, most of our testers preferred skillets that weighed between 2 and 3½ pounds, which were still light enough for tossing ingredients in a pan without placing too much torque on their wrists. We took the advice of our pros and looked at many cookware sets in person before testing, to get a feel for the weight and the actual size of the pots and pans. Getting a sense of each set just by looking at pictures online is difficult.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Additionally, we limited our search to cookware with sloped sides. Some skillets, such as this ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"class":"product-link","href":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/14014/40138/4/59242/?merchant=Wayfair","rel":"nofollow noopener","target":"_blank","data-gtm-trigger":"product_link","data-store":"Wayfair","data-vars-store":"Wayfair","data-vars-outbound-link":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/14014/40138/4/59242/?merchant=Wayfair"},"children":[{"data":"Viking Contemporary Frying Pan","type":"text"}]},{"data":", have sharply angled sides that make tossing vegetables while sautéing difficult.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"h3","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Durability and even heat distribution","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Ideally, we wanted sets of fully clad tri-ply stainless steel, which has an aluminum core sandwiched between layers of stainless steel extending up the sides of the pan. Fully clad tri-ply stainless steel is the best option for both pros and home cooks because of its even heat distribution (aluminum heats up quickly and distributes heat well; steel is very durable and holds heat nicely). It’s also very durable and dishwasher safe. Unlike aluminum, stainless steel is nonreactive to acidic ingredients like tomatoes or vinegar, so it won’t leave behind a metallic taste. And unlike nonstick cookware, you can use stainless steel pans over high heat and move them directly from the stovetop to the oven. Bottom line: Good-quality stainless steel pans are buy-it-for-life items.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"In addition to making tri-ply cookware, most high-end manufacturers produce sets that are made from five or more layers of stainless steel, aluminum, and sometimes copper. With each additional layer, the pans become more expensive. In most of our tests, five-ply cookware didn’t heat as uniformly as regular tri-ply cookware, or the differences were negligible. One exception was the ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"class":"product-link","href":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17441/165614/4/74843/?merchant=Amazon","rel":"nofollow noopener","target":"_blank","data-gtm-trigger":"product_link","data-store":"Amazon","data-vars-store":"Amazon","data-vars-outbound-link":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/17441/165614/4/74843/?merchant=Amazon"},"children":[{"data":"Demeyere 5-Plus 10-Piece Cookware Set","type":"text"}]},{"data":", which heated impressively evenly. That said, the pans in this set took longer to heat up than those in the All-Clad set. Five-ply cookware also holds onto more heat, so it’s slower to react when you lower the heat on your stove. Ultimately, we don’t think the extra cost of five-ply cookware is worth it.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"shortcode-pullquote","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Fully clad tri-ply stainless steel is the best option for both pros and home cooks because of its even heat distribution.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"We did our best to avoid sets that aren’t fully clad, meaning the aluminum core doesn’t extend up the sides of the cookware, because they’re prone to scorching. However, if you’re looking for a cheap set, cookware with tri-ply disks welded to the bottom of the pan (also called encapsulated bottoms) will distribute heat more evenly than pans made from a single piece of stainless steel. In our experience, sets with encapsulated bottoms performed better than those that had just a single layer of stainless steel, but we still wouldn’t recommend them. Fully clad tri-ply cookware is the way to go.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"shortcode-caption","attribs":{"id":"attachment_11286","align":"alignnone","width":"630"},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"img","attribs":{"class":"size-full wp-image-11286","src":"https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272.jpg","alt":"a comparison of two pots as part of our cookware sets testing process","width":"630","height":"420","noInlineStyles":false},"children":[],"dbData":{"width":630,"height":420,"sources":[{"path":"2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272.jpg","width":630,"height":420},{"path":"2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272-300x200.jpg","width":300,"height":200},{"path":"2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272-570x380.jpg","width":570,"height":380},{"path":"2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272-330x220.jpg","width":330,"height":220},{"path":"2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272-200x134.jpg","width":200,"height":134},{"path":"2017/08/cookwear-lowres-5272-120x80.jpg","width":120,"height":80}]}},{"data":" Our testers preferred cookware that’s fully clad, such as the Tramontina saucepan (right), as opposed to pans with encapsulated bottoms, like the Cuisinart Chef’s Classic saucepan (left), which are prone to scorching on the sides.","type":"text"}],"dbData":{"credit":"Photo: Michael Hession"}},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"h3","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Materials to avoid","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"ul","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"li","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"strong","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Aluminum","type":"text"}]},{"data":" is reactive to acidic foods and can give them a metallic taste. It’s also not induction cooktop compatible. (Because induction burners transfer heat through a magnetic field, cookware must contain sufficient amounts of iron, such as cast iron or magnetic stainless steel, in order to be compatible.)","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"ty