ecutter/blog/how-to-clean-stainless-steel-pans/"},"children":[{"data":"blog post","type":"text"}]},{"data":" and ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P16xnzCWiec","rel":"noopener","target":"_blank"},"children":[{"data":"video","type":"text"}]},{"data":" on the subject.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Never clean your stainless steel cookware with harsh chemicals, such as oven cleaner, that could cause permanent damage. Also, avoid using steel wool, which can severely scratch your cookware.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"It’s industry standard for cookware manufacturers to advise against cooking over high temperatures to avoid liability for damage caused by misuse. However, judging from our years of experience, as long as you reduce the heat after preheating your pan on medium or medium-high heat, you won’t damage your pans.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"For information on how to prevent food from sticking to your stainless steel cookware, check out our ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/blog/food-sticking-pan/"},"children":[{"data":"blog post","type":"text"}]},{"data":" on the subject.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"If you’re worried about using metal utensils on your stainless steel cookware, don’t be: Although such tools may cause minor scratches on the surface of pots and pans, they will not damage the cookware’s performance.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Also, don’t place a screaming-hot pan under running water or in a sink to soak. Chef Janet Crandall told us, “I can’t stress enough